        "paragraph_index": 0,
        "text": "## Stability-Constant Measurements at 25 °C in SRD-46\n\n| Condition | Count | Percentage |\n|-----------|------:|----------:|\n| Measured at 25 °C | 67,237 | **85.0%** |\n| All other temperatures | 11,826 | 15.0% |\n| **Total measurements** | **79,063** | **100%** |\n\n**85.0% of all stability-constant measurements** in the NIST SRD-46 database were conducted at 25 °C.\n\nThis overwhelming preference for 25 °C (298.15 K) is standard practice in solution thermodynamics — it is the conventional reference temperature for reporting equilibrium constants, and most experimental setups (thermostated baths, calorimeters) default to it. The remaining ~15% at other temperatures are valuable for deriving enthalpy and entropy of complexation via van 't Hoff analysis, but they are comparatively scarce.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
